The paper deals with learning to rank in complex settings where the display order is not known beforehand. This involves both traditional ranking and inferring the best display order. Therefore, the paper is likely to belong to the Information Retrieval (cs.IR) and Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper deals with user preferences and layouts, which suggests that it could also belong to the Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC) and Computational Linguistics (cs.CL) sub-categories. Finally, the paper uses deep reinforcement learning and sequential selection, which suggests that it could also belong to the Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition (cs.CV) sub-category.
